By 6:00 am local time, Tahrir Square was quiet, with only a few hundred people.<ref name="aj-liveblog30jan">{{cite web|url=http://blogs.aljazeera.net/middle-east/2011/01/29/live-blog-301-egypt-protests|title=Live Blog 30/1 â Egypt Protests|work=[[Al Jazeera English]]|date=30 January 2011|accessdate=30 January 2011}}</ref> Later in the morning, 3â5,000 protesters were reported as gathering there, including hundreds of state judges protesting for the first time.<ref name="aj-liveblog30jan" /><ref>[http://twitter.com/#!/nolanjourno Dan Nolan @nolanjazeera].</ref><ref name="Egypt's opposition discusses interim government">{{Cite news|url=http://www.almasryalyoum.com/en/node/307700|title=Egypt's Opposition Discusses Interim Government|work=[[Almasry Alyoum]]|date=30 January 2011|accessdate=30 January 2011}}</ref> They called for a new [[Constitution of Egypt|constitution]] and a [[transitional government]].
Soldiers were then ordered to use [[live ammunition]], but the army refused the order since it was present to "protect the people". The army chief told protesters they would not be fired upon. Helicopters monitored the protests, and [[fighter jet]]s repeatedly flew low over Tahrir Square.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://english.aljazeera.net/news/middleeast/2011/01/201113033817859936.html|title=Cairo Protesters Stand Their Ground|work=[[Al Jazeera English]]|date=30 January 2011|accessdate=30 January 2011}}</ref> After the first pass of the two [[Egyptian Air Force]] [[F-16]]s, the crowd cheered and subsequent passes triggered louder chants, laughing, and waving. The crowd did not disperse.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.usatoday.com/news/world/2011-01-30-egypt-protests_N.htm|title=Egyptian Demonstrations Calm Down|work=[[USA Today]]|last=Michaels|first=Jim|date=30 January 2011|accessdate=30 January 2011}}</ref> Protesters were also reported picking up garbage in Tahrir Square, as essential services were not working and that they wanted to "keep our country clean".
